This attitude and this political context represent, as it were, the necessity, the ἀνάγκη, that often fetters heroes of Greek tragedy. In the debate with the priest the role of jephthah is not unlike that of Creon in Sophocles' Antigone. And the tragedy ofJephthah’s fate is transcended by the sadness implied in Buchanan’s message: the sadness of a more ratio- nalistic biblical-humanistic ethics, which is aware of it's own weak position in sixteenth century society.

The drama as a whole, then, is not built up from the units of individua] characters confronted with realistic situations or problems. Itis rather an ongoing debate between emotions and ideas, each of which is embodied in a particular character or the chorus, in a particular episode or an ode.⁷
